I’m so excited to finally announce that we are going to be back in person for my end of year mental health retreat in Dallas Texas Dec 2-4! 

This years conference is all about helping you manage your mental health and clean up the post-Covid mental mess! 

I’ll be doing sessions on trauma recovery, healing anxiety, unwiring toxic thinking habits and more. Plus we will have amazing guest speakers, VIP workshops, swag bags, and so much more! And we will be offering CMEs and CEUS!

This is a retreat not just for mental health and medical professionals. It’s for parents, teachers, students, grandparents, athletes, everyone! Because mental health is a universal concern.

node.text:
We spend so much time warning our kids about the dangers of substances, yet spend little time teaching them how to manage their mental health so they can manage all that life brings. 

We won’t ever be able to end substance abuse until we help people learn how to manage their minds and self-regulate their minds and nervous systems. We have to address the root not just the symptoms. 

Dr. Nicole said is best: the “gateway” drug is childhood trauma and a unregulated mind.

node.text:
Time for some honest reflection and deep digging: are you doing something that is slowing your growth and healing because it feels familiar and safe?

If so that’s normal and understandable, and you may need to be where you are for a time. But don’t stay there or avoid moving forward because it is unfamiliar and doesn’t feel good. 

It’s key to learn to recognize the different types of feeling uncomfortable because sometimes it is a real signal helping you avoid danger, and sometimes your body and mind is just resisting change that’s necessary because it doesn’t yet have the neural networks in place. 

Learning to tune into your mind, emotions, physical sensations, and thoughts will help you learn how to distinguish between the different uncomfortable feelings and help you recognize when to stay and when to go. This is all part of self-regulation, self-awareness, and going beyond mindfulness. 

Some helpful tips when working through uncomfortable and unfamiliar feelings:
1. Practice mindfulness through prayer, meditation, etc. 
2. Talk to a friend or therapist 
3. Remember: this is good for you and part of healing. You have to feel in order to heal!
4. Balance out the hard work with some fun and laughter!

I’ll be talking more about this topic in-depth at my 2021 mental health retreat in Dallas, TX Dec 2-4! Get your tickets here: https://www.drleafconference.com (tap the link in my bio)
